## IDS Icons - Design System Asset Library

`@design-systems/icons` is the Intuit Design System (IDS) asset library for SVG icons. Icons are provided as React components that can be imported and used directly in your application.

**Important**: Use `@design-systems/icons` for all icon needs.

[IDS Icon Search Tool](https://icons.app.intuit.com/search)

[IDS Icons Repository](https://github.intuit.com/design-systems/icons)

[IDS Badge Component Documentation](https://github.intuit.com/design-systems/ids-web/tree/next/components/Badge)

## Usage Workflow

When you need to add an icon to a component, follow this workflow:

1. Check if a Badge component is more appropriate (see "Badges vs Icons" section below)
2. Verify the icon exists by searching at https://icons.app.intuit.com/search
3. Check if `@design-systems/icons` is installed in package.json
4. Install if needed: `yarn add @design-systems/icons`
5. Import the icon using PascalCase naming
6. Use the icon directly as a React component
7. If the icon is not found, inform the user and suggest alternatives (do not create custom SVG files)

## Icon Naming Convention

Icons are exported as PascalCase React components. The source SVG files use lowercase with dashes but are automatically transformed to PascalCase component names during the build process.

**Naming rules:**

- Icons use PascalCase (e.g., `PersonCalculator`, `Upload`, `CheckCircle`)
- Icon names do not include the word "Icon" as a suffix
- Partial icons use PascalCase with "Partial" suffix (e.g., `UploadPartial` from `upload-partial.svg`)

**Correct imports:**

```jsx
import { PersonCalculator, Upload, CheckCircle } from "@design-systems/icons";
import { UploadPartial, CheckCirclePartial } from "@design-systems/icons";
```

**Incorrect imports (these exports do not exist):**

```jsx
import { PersonCalculatorIcon, UploadIcon } from "@design-systems/icons";
import { personCalculator, upload } from "@design-systems/icons";
```

If you prefer having "Icon" in your variable names, you can rename on import:

```jsx
import {
  PersonCalculator as PersonCalculatorIcon,
  Upload as UploadIcon,
} from "@design-systems/icons";
```

## Finding Icons

Always use the Icon Search App to verify icon availability before importing:

https://icons.app.intuit.com/search

You can search by icon name, meta tags, or visual appearance.

**If an icon is not found:**

1. Double-check the search tool using synonyms or related terms
2. Inform the user that the specific icon is not available in `@design-systems/icons`
3. Suggest similar available icons from the search results
4. Do not create custom SVG files, use img tags with SVG sources, or use third-party icon libraries as alternatives

## Badges vs Icons

**When to use a Badge**: If a Badge exists for your use case, use `@ids-ts/badge` instead of importing an icon directly.

See the Badge documentation for supported Badge icons: https://github.intuit.com/design-systems/ids-web/tree/next/components/Badge#badge-icons

If you believe a Badge is missing, post in #ask-ids on Slack or consider contributing to @ids-ts.

## Icon Partials

Some icons are suffixed with `-partial` in their source files (e.g., `upload-partial.svg` exports as `UploadPartial`). These are scaled to be approximately 1/2 the size of a standard icon within the same viewbox, designed to be layered on top of background shapes.

Common use case: Badge components where a partial icon is layered on top of shapes like `Circle` or `Triangle`.

```jsx
import { UploadPartial, Circle } from "@design-systems/icons";

<div style={{ position: 'relative' }}>
  <Circle size="large" color="var(--color-background-info)" />
  <UploadPartial size="large" color="var(--color-text-inverse)" />
</div>
```

## How do I install IDS Icons?

**Before installing, check if `@design-systems/icons` is already in package.json.**

```sh
yarn add @design-systems/icons
```

The package is resolved from the Intuit npm registry configured in `.yarnrc.yml`.

**Code Snippet for IDS Icons**

Then to use icons in your code just import them:

```jsx
import { PersonCalculator, Upload } from "@design-systems/icons";

// Use the icon directly as a component
const IconExample = () => (
  <div>
    <PersonCalculator />
    <Upload />
  </div>
);

export default IconExample;
```

## Icon Props

All icons from `@design-systems/icons` accept the following props:

| Prop Name | Type   | Options                                                    | Default        |
| --------- | ------ | ---------------------------------------------------------- | -------------- |
| size      | string | 'xsmall', 'small', 'medium', 'large', 'xlarge', 'xxlarge' | 'medium'       |
| color     | string | any string (recommend using design tokens)                 | 'currentColor' |

**Examples:**

```jsx
// Medium icon with default color
<PersonCalculator />

// Large icon with custom color using design token
<Upload size="large" color="var(--color-action-standard)" />

// Small icon with currentColor (inherits from parent text color)
<Upload size="small" />
```

## Best Practices

**Do:**

- Always use `@design-systems/icons` for all icon needs
- Import icons as named exports using PascalCase names
- Use design tokens for color (prefer `var(--color-*)` tokens over hardcoded hex/rgb values)
- Use `currentColor` when appropriate (this allows icons to inherit text color from parent elements)
- Check for Badges first before using an icon directly (see Badges vs Icons section)
- Verify icon existence using https://icons.app.intuit.com/search before importing
- Use semantic size names ('small', 'medium', 'large') not pixel values

**Do not:**

- Never create custom SVG files or inline SVG code as alternatives to missing icons
- Never use `<img src="icon.svg">` or other image tags for icons
- Never use icon fonts (FontAwesome, Material Icons, etc.)
- Never use third-party icon libraries (heroicons, lucide, etc.)
- Never use the deprecated `@ids-ts/icon` wrapper component
- Never hardcode pixel sizes (use the size prop instead)
- Never assume an icon exists (always verify in the search tool first)

## Common Patterns

**Icon with adjacent text:**

```jsx
import { Upload } from "@design-systems/icons";

<button style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 'var(--space-100)' }}>
  <Upload size="small" />
  <span>Upload File</span>
</button>
```

**Icon inheriting text color:**

```jsx
import { Upload } from "@design-systems/icons";

<div style={{ color: 'var(--color-action-standard)' }}>
  <Upload />
  <span>Upload</span>
</div>
```

**Icon with specific color:**

```jsx
import { Upload } from "@design-systems/icons";

<Upload 
  size="medium" 
  color="var(--color-status-error)" 
/>
```

